The L5AWM fills the gap between the current metal and polymer magazine designs combing the best features from both designs into a unique hybrid magazine. L5AWM has the reliability of a steel magazine, the durability of a polymer magazine and the weight of an aluminum magazine.

Unique to the AWM is the one piece wrap around hardened steel feed lip assembly that is permanently attached to an impact resistant polymer body. The hardened steel feed lips won’t bend, break or deform due to rough handling or long term storage. An aggressive surface texture has been applied to the polymer body to improve gripping and retrieval from pouches. The combination of steel and polymer result in a lightweight, robust magazine tough enough for professional use.

The internal geometry of the Advanced Warfighter Magazine is a constant curve that has been maximized to feed the 5.56X45mm NATO round and has a non-tilting follower for trouble-free feeding. The feed lips are made from a single piece of precision formed steel that is hardened, then PTFE coated for corrosion resistance. The body and component materials are corrosion and chemical resistant, passing military chemical testing, including exposure to DEET.

The L5 AWM is compatible with modern weapon systems; M4/M16/AR, HK416, SCAR16, and the ARX160 to name a few.

title: For Sale:  HOUSE BILL BANS EXISTING MAG TRANSFERS
location: TRANSFER OF MAGAZINES TO BE BANNED, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Congresswoman Diana Degette (D) CO, has introduced legislation in the House of Representatives which would ban the manufacture, transfer and possession of new magazines over 10 rounds capacity. Existing magazines would be grandfathered HOWEVER you would be prohibited from ever transferring them even to family members. If this passes you are stuck with them and can no longer sell YOUR OWN PROPERTY. A perfect example of how the second amendment is not the only right these people spit on with regularity. This is basically the McCarthy Magazine bill from last session dug up and trotted out again. This measure has numerous democratic sponsors and they are trying to force it to the floor for a vote ASAP.  The gun banners know that if they can get this legislation to a vote while emotions are still running high after Sandy Hook they have a good chance of passing it. That chance decreases every day. Please write house speaker Boehner and demand that this bill NOT be allowed to the House floor for a vote. Anyone can write the speaker, you do not need to be in his district or even in his state. Suggested text follows at the end of this post if you agree with it, use it as is, if not change whatever you don't agree with. You can do this in about 1% of the time it now takes to find a single reasonably priced high cap mag. Just fill out the contact form, cut and paste, or pick up the phone and call, or, better yet do both.

http://www.speaker.gov/contact

You should also contact your local congressman/woman. You can get the contact info here just by entering a zip code:

http://www.nraila.org/get-involved-locally/grassroots/write-your-reps.aspx

SUGGESTED TEXT TO THE SPEAKER

Dear Speaker Boehner,

I am writing you regarding the numerous gun control measures currently being circulated in congress, and the Diana Degette - D CO, magazine ban in particular. This measure would place severe restrictions on magazines over 10 rounds in capacity. These magazines are used by 10's of millions of law abiding Americans.  I STRONGLY oppose these gun control measures and this measure specifically. They do not make us safer and do nothing but disarm and hamstring those who obey laws, while criminals simply ignore the laws in their entirety. A magazine ban will do NOTHING to prevent crime or mass shootings which are a statistically rare event, and have essentially 0 effect on our overall violent crime rate. After studying the effects of the 1994 ban on "assault" weapons and high capacity magazines the USDOJ concluded in parrt: “At best, the assault weapons ban can have only a limited effect on total gun murders, because the banned weapons and magazines were never involved in more than a modest fraction of all gun murders." The time required to change a magazine is trivial. I can do it in about a second and I'm slow. 

The 10's of millions of law abiding gun owners in this country are NOT the problem and we are frankly becoming very tired of being treated as though we are. The real problem is that these horrific shootings occur in so called "gun free" zones where the victims, or in the case of children, those responsible for protecting them, are disarmed and unable to mount any effective defense. When this is the case, the weapon used, and how many rounds of ammunition it holds, is frankly trivial. Any reasonably effective weapon can be used to kill large numbers of unarmed and helpless people. 

The short term, direct solution to these senseless and horrific acts is ARMED security in our schools NOW. Law enforcement officers are already in many schools and they should be in all of them. If the individuals who commit these acts knew that they would be confronted by an immediate armed response the number of attempts at these sort of mass killings would decrease dramatically. Compare the Sandy Hook tragedy, where nobody but the killer was armed, to the 1997 Pearl Mississippi school shooting where Vice Principal Joel Myrick was able to retrieve his handgun from his truck (it was illegal for him to possess or carry it in the school) and apprehend the shooter, Luke Woodham without Myrick firing a single shot. Luke Woodham's admitted plan after attacking his high school, was to go to the local Jr. High and continue his rampage there. Myrick stopped that plan cold. Unfortunately, there was no ARMED Joel Myrick at Sandy Hook. In another incident, in 2001, senior Jason Hoffman opened fire at Granite Hills High School in El Cajon, California. Hoffman wounded five people before being shot and incapacitated by, ARMED school resource officer (a police officer) Richard Agundez. An ARMED response to these incidents works, when it is in place. These individuals may not be afraid to die but they are afraid of arrest and prison. This is why they typically commit suicide rather than be taken into custody. The arguments against having the same armed police officers who enforce the laws and provide protection in the rest of society in schools are absurd. That includes the arguments against the cost. We could pay for an armed police officer in every school simply by cutting the foreign aid to countries where most of the population hates us. We have paid billions in aid to Pakistan, apparently, to hide Osama Bin Laden next to a military base. The money would be better spent protecting our own people right here in America.

The long term solution is to improve our mental health systems and address the real problem: The tendency toward violence in our society.

With regard to the Degette legislation I do not believe that this legislation should be allowed to come to a vote at this time. This is an obvious ploy to play on people's emotions immediately following a national tragedy. I am asking that you, as speaker, block this measure from coming to the house floor. The Senate routinely blocks legislation from being voted upon, in fact Harry Reid does so with monotonous regularity, and there is no reason the house should not do the same with regard to bills like this one. If the measure does come to a vote, please know this: American gun owners are a large part of the GOP constituency. You cannot win elections without us and as one of these gun owners I want this legislation defeated by any and all means at your disposal.

Sincerely,

END SUGGESTED TEXT

"Raven MP-25 has a tumultuous history and remains a controversial piece of the American firearms scene. It was designed by the famous George Jennings, and is the original, quintessential, “Saturday night special.” Reviled by journalists and anti-crime activists for its extreme popularity with criminals, this weapon suffered a smear campaign unrivaled until the concept of the “scary black rifle” reared its ugly head in the nineties. While it is true that criminals employed this weapon heavily through the seventies (count how many you see in the movies “Dolemite” or “Black Caesar”), it was the same things that attracted the weapon to criminals that attracted it to everyone else. For twenty years, this pocket stinger ruled the streets of Miami, Memphis, and Harlem. It was designed to be small, light and disposable. In the end, like any weapon, it has good points and bad, and the end user must ultimately make the decision for their own reasons...
This weapon only had one competitor in its class when it came out: the Colt .38 Detective special. In the sixties, the snub-nosed .38 ruled the concealed weapon scene. Small, comparatively powerful, and reliable, every cop had one on the ankle and every detective had one on the hip. When the MP-25 hit, you now had access to a weapon that could shoot seven rounds and then reload in the blink of an eye. Like all detachable magazine automatics, reloading is as simple as dropping the mag, and sliding in another. It was way faster than wrestling a speed-loader into a revolver, or worse, feeding individual rounds into the cylinder..."

title: For Sale:  FNH FN USA FNAR 16" Carbine AR 308 / 7.62 Nato NIB
location: MOSCOW MILLS MO, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
FNH USA FNAR Rifle
Gas-operated semi-auto .308 Win. tactical rifle based on Browning’s BAR ShortTrac. 
The FNAR is a gas-operated semi-automatic .308 Win. tactical rifle based on Browning’s BAR ShortTrac semi-automatic rifle. Designed to be a short- to medium-range rifle, the FNAR is available in both light- and heavy-barrel variants, the latter being about a pound heavier than the former. All models accept proprietary FN 10- and 20-round magazines. THIS NEW GUN IS PRE-BAN WITH 1 FACTORY 20 RD MAG! 

A simple philosophy guided the development of the FNAR: to provide autoloading speed along with bolt-action accuracy. The FNAR is guaranteed to group into 1 m.o.a. or less with the proper ammunition. Contributing to this is the rifle’s 18-inch chrome-molybdenum steel barrel, with cold-hammer-forged rifling in a 1:12-inch four-groove, right-hand twist. Both bore and chamber are hard-chromed for durability. The chamber is cut to SAAMI specifications for the commercial .308 Win., but is also optimized for the use of 7.62x51 mm NATO ammunition as well. The muzzle has a recessed, target-style crown. The chamber end of the barrel terminates in an integral extension that is clamped firmly in the receiver ring and contains recesses for the bolt head’s locking lugs. Both the light- and heavy profile barrels have six flutes and a matte black finish. The split-ring clamping system that retains the barrel in the receiver allows for a solid barrel/receiver joint and facilitates barrel changes by armorers. 

The FNAR’s gas system is essentially the same as that of the BAR. Propellant gas is bled from a port in the barrel about 9¼-inches forward of the receiver ring, and enters the gas cylinder affixed to the underside of the barrel inside the fore-end. The gas impels the gas piston assembly 3/8-inch to the rear, which, in turn, pushes on the inertia block and action bars, which run into the receiver to connect to the bolt carrier. As the carrier moves rearward, the bolt head is cammed counterclockwise until its lugs unlock from the barrel extension, the empty case is extracted and ejected, the action spring beneath the barrel is compressed, and the hammer is cocked. Returning forward, the bolt and carrier strip the top round from the magazine and feed it into the chamber, and the bolt head enters the barrel extension and rotates clockwise to lock the action. 

A novel feature of the FNAR is the bolt-forward indicator, a red dot on the bottom edge of the ejection port that is visible only when the bolt is fully forward and locked into the barrel extension. 

The trigger group is retained in the receiver by two crosspins. The two-stage trigger is factory-set from 3.25 pounds to 5.5 pounds, and is not user-adjustable. Just rearward of the trigger guard is a crossbolt safety that, when engaged, locks the trigger. The safety can be reversed for left-handed shooters. 

Forward of the trigger group is the generous beveled magazine well, a separate piece attached to the underside of the receiver. Release of the FNAR’s magazine is by way of ambidextrous checkered buttons at the rear of the well. 

In order to meet the minimum factory standard of 10,000 rounds with no breakages, every major component and system of the FNAR was designed to be stronger and more durable than its counterpart on the BAR. 

Law enforcement input in the development of the FNAR is evident in the 9¾-inch-long Picatinny rail atop the receiver, as well as in the gun’s non-reflective black synthetic stock. The fore-end features three 4 3/8-inch-long Picatinny rail sections, with the bottom rail having a stud for sling or bipod attachment.
